[[Lieutenant-General (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-General]] '''Sir Ronald MacKenzie Scobie''' [[Order of the British Empire|KBE]], [[Order of the Bath|CB]], [[Military Cross|MC]] (8 June 1893 - 1969) was a [[British Army]] officer who commanded [[III Corps (United Kingdom)|III Corps]].

==Military career==
Educated at [[Cheltenham]] and [[Woolwich]], Scobie played [[rugby football|rugby]] for [[Scotland]] in 1914. He was commissioned into the [[Royal Engineers]] in 1914 and served in [[World War I]].<ref name=lh>[http://www.kcl.ac.uk/lhcma/locreg/SCOBIE.shtml Liddell Hart Centre for Military Archives]</ref> He became Director of Military Artillery at the Royal Military College, Australia in 1932 and Assistant Adjutant General at the [[War Office]] in 1938.<ref name=lh/>

In 1939, at the start of [[World War II]] Scobie, a brigadier, was Deputy Director of Mobilisation at the [[War Office]].<ref name=lh/> After this he held the position Deputy Adjutant General at General Headquarters, [[Middle East Land Forces]] in 1940 before being given command of the [[70th Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|70th Infantry Division]],<ref name=lh/> which was sent into to relieve the [[9th Division (Australia)|Australian 9th Division]] in [[Tobruk]]. Scobie was in command of the Tobruk fortress from 22 October 1941 to 13 December 1941, when, as part of [[Operation Crusader]], the 70th Infantry Division led the successful break-out from Tobruk. In 1942 he became General Officer Commanding the Troops in [[Malta]] and on 22 March 1943 Scobie was promoted to [[lieutenant general]] and made Chief of the General Staff at General Headquarters Middle East.<ref name=lh/> From 11 December 1943 he was given command of [[III Corps (United Kingdom)|III Corps]]<ref>{{oob person | id = 869 | name = Ronald Scobie }}</ref> which was sent to [[Greece]] to expel the Germans but ended up becoming involved in the [[Greek Civil War]]. He remained in command of British forces in Greece until 1946.<ref name=lh/> He retired in 1947.<ref name=lh/>

